docs.abstract: Shareholders are voting on whether to push the tech giant to examine the human rights and financial risks of the surveillance technology.
docs.snippet: Shareholders are voting on whether to push the tech giant to examine the human rights and financial risks of the surveillance technology.
docs.lead_paragraph: Facial recognition software is coming under increasing scrutiny from civil liberties groups and lawmakers. Now Amazon, one of the most visible purveyors of the technology, is facing pressure from another corner as well: its own shareholders.

headline.main: Amazon Faces Investor Pressure Over Facial Recognition
headline.print_headline: Investors Pressure Amazon Over Facial Recognition

docs.abstract: In a free service, bots call restaurants and make reservations. The technology is impressive, except for when the caller is actually a person.
docs.snippet: In a free service, bots call restaurants and make reservations. The technology is impressive, except for when the caller is actually a person.
docs.lead_paragraph: ALBANY, Calif. — On a recent afternoon at the Lao Thai Kitchen restaurant, the telephone rang and the caller ID read “Google Assistant.” Jimmy Tran, a waiter, answered the phone. The caller was a man with an Irish accent hoping to book a dinner reservation for two on the weekend.

headline.main: Google’s Duplex Uses A.I. to Mimic Humans (Sometimes)
headline.print_headline: A Bot Can Book You a Table, or Maybe Not

byline.original: By Brian X. Chen and Cade Metz

docs.abstract: The resolutions, voted on by shareholders, would have pushed the company to reconsider its societal impact.
docs.snippet: The resolutions, voted on by shareholders, would have pushed the company to reconsider its societal impact.
docs.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — Amazon said on Wednesday that its shareholders had voted down proposals that would have pushed the company to reconsider its societal impact in two key areas: facial recognition and climate change.

headline.main: Amazon Investors Reject Proposals on Climate Change and Facial Recognition

docs.abstract: Streaming services have revolutionized the discovery of songs, but here’s why Ben Sisario, who covers the music industry, still likes to listen to compact discs.
docs.snippet: Streaming services have revolutionized the discovery of songs, but here’s why Ben Sisario, who covers the music industry, still likes to listen to compact discs.
docs.lead_paragraph: How do New York Times journalists use technology in their jobs and in their personal lives? Ben Sisario, a reporter who covers the music industry, discussed the tech he’s using.

headline.main: Why Play a Music CD? ‘No Ads, No Privacy Terrors, No Algorithms’
headline.print_headline: Poking Around Music Platforms, but Favoring CDs

docs.abstract: After putting three magazines up for sale last year, the publisher strikes a deal said to be worth $35 million. The longtime Golf Digest editor Jerry Tarde will stay.
docs.snippet: After putting three magazines up for sale last year, the publisher strikes a deal said to be worth $35 million. The longtime Golf Digest editor Jerry Tarde will stay.
docs.lead_paragraph: Condé Nast has sold Golf Digest to Discovery Inc., the companies said on Monday, as the publisher of The New Yorker, Vanity Fair and Vogue sheds titles amid recent losses related to the decline of the magazine business.

headline.main: Condé Nast Sells Golf Digest to Discovery Inc.
headline.print_headline: Condé Nast in Deal to Sell Golf Digest for $35 Million

docs.abstract: Earlier this year, we set out to photograph a certain kind of place: spaces rarely seen by the public, where decisions are made and power is exercised.
docs.snippet: Earlier this year, we set out to photograph a certain kind of place: spaces rarely seen by the public, where decisions are made and power is exercised.
docs.lead_paragraph: The spaces where decisions are made and power is exercised are rarely seen by the public. Five photographers explored these rooms, where global policy is discussed and fine art is priced. The pictures delve into the spaces of influencers — absent the decision makers themselves. Their energy and personalities linger in the surroundings.

docs.abstract: The network promotes TV veterans (Fran Drescher! Brian Williams!) while noting that it’s pushing back the start date of its streaming service.
docs.snippet: The network promotes TV veterans (Fran Drescher! Brian Williams!) while noting that it’s pushing back the start date of its streaming service.
docs.lead_paragraph: The TV industry is unveiling its coming season to advertisers in Manhattan this week, at a series of events known as the upfronts. Three New York Times media reporters — John Koblin, Michael M. Grynbaum and Edmund Lee — assess the NBC presentation at Radio City Music Hall on Monday, the first from the four major broadcast networks.

headline.main: NBC Makes a Nostalgic Pitch to Advertisers at Radio City

byline.original: By John Koblin, Michael M. Grynbaum and Edmund Lee

docs.abstract: In a tense meeting with American Airlines pilots shortly after the first deadly crash of Boeing’s new jet, executives insisted that the plane was safe to fly.
docs.snippet: In a tense meeting with American Airlines pilots shortly after the first deadly crash of Boeing’s new jet, executives insisted that the plane was safe to fly.
docs.lead_paragraph: Weeks after the first fatal crash of the 737 Max, pilots from American Airlines pressed Boeing executives to work urgently on a fix. In a closed-door meeting, they even argued that Boeing should push authorities to take an emergency measure that would likely result in the grounding of the Max.

headline.main: Before Ethiopian Crash, Boeing Resisted Pilots’ Calls for Aggressive Steps on 737 Max
headline.print_headline: Boeing Resisted Pilots’ Calls for Urgent Fix of Jet

docs.lead_paragraph: The Walt Disney Company has agreed to acquire Comcast’s one-third stake in Hulu and to take full control of the streaming service, the companies said on Tuesday.
